1
00:01:00,102 --> 00:01:02,104
[BANGING]

2
00:01:04,398 --> 00:01:06,108
What the fuck is that?

3
00:01:06,817 --> 00:01:07,985
<i>Jimmy?</i>

4
00:01:08,277 --> 00:01:10,028
- What's up?
- Did I hit something?

5
00:01:10,195 --> 00:01:11,863
What the fuck is that?

6
00:01:12,906 --> 00:01:14,533
Maybe you got a flat?

7
00:01:15,409 --> 00:01:17,661
Wha--? No.

8
00:01:19,288 --> 00:01:21,248
What the fuck? You better pull over and see.

9
00:01:26,920 --> 00:01:28,922
[BANGING]

10
00:01:46,857 --> 00:01:48,108
[STAMMERING]

11
00:01:48,400 --> 00:01:50,652
He's still alive. You fucking piece of shit!

12
00:01:50,819 --> 00:01:53,655
Die, you motherfucker! Look at me!

13
00:02:03,123 --> 00:02:07,085
HENRY: <i>As far back as I can remember,
I always wanted to be a gangster.</i>

14
00:02:47,042 --> 00:02:48,085
<i>To me...</i>

15
00:02:48,251 --> 00:02:52,506
<i>...being a gangster was better than
being president of the United States.</i>

16
00:02:55,801 --> 00:02:59,346
<i>Even before I first wandered
into the cabstand for an after-school job...</i>

17
00:02:59,513 --> 00:03:01,598
<i>I knew I wanted to be a part of them.</i>

18
00:03:01,765 --> 00:03:04,184
<i>It was there that I knew I belonged.</i>

19
00:03:04,351 --> 00:03:08,855
<i>To me, it meant being somebody
in a neighbourhood full of nobodies.</i>

20
00:03:09,022 --> 00:03:12,109
<i>They weren't like anybody else.
They did whatever they wanted.</i>

21
00:03:12,275 --> 00:03:15,862
<i>They double-parked in front of a hydrant,
nobody ever gave them a ticket.</i>

22
00:03:16,029 --> 00:03:18,240
<i>In the summer,
when they played cards all night...</i>

23
00:03:18,407 --> 00:03:20,659
<i>...nobody ever called the cops.</i>

24
00:03:22,285 --> 00:03:24,121
[MEN CHATTERING]

25
00:03:32,838 --> 00:03:34,715
MAN: Tony Stacks. How are you?

26
00:03:36,007 --> 00:03:37,509
HENRY: <i>Tuddy Cicero.</i>

27
00:03:37,676 --> 00:03:39,928
Could this be the Canarsie Kid?

28
00:03:40,554 --> 00:03:42,097
- How are you?
- Good.

29
00:03:43,390 --> 00:03:44,558
HENRY: <i>Tuddy.</i>

30
00:03:45,475 --> 00:03:48,520
<i>Tuddy ran the cabstand
and the Bella Vista Pizzeria...</i>

31
00:03:48,687 --> 00:03:53,316
<i>and other places for his brother, Paul,
who was the boss of the neighborhood.</i>

32
00:03:53,817 --> 00:03:55,819
[LAUGHING]

33
00:03:57,946 --> 00:04:00,240
<i>Paulie might have moved slow...</i>

34
00:04:02,701 --> 00:04:06,663
<i>but it was only because Paulie
didn't have to move for anybody.</i>

35
00:04:11,334 --> 00:04:12,961
- It's your fault.
- You started it.

36
00:04:13,128 --> 00:04:15,172
I started it? It's your fault.

37
00:04:15,338 --> 00:04:17,507
HENRY: <i>At first my parents loved
that I found a job...</i>

38
00:04:17,674 --> 00:04:19,760
<i>across the street from the house.</i>

39
00:04:20,886 --> 00:04:24,639
<i>My father, who was Irish,
was sent to work at the age of 11.</i>

40
00:04:24,931 --> 00:04:26,725
<i>He liked that I got myself a job.</i>

41
00:04:26,892 --> 00:04:30,437
<i>He always used to say
that American kids were spoiled lazy.</i>

42
00:04:32,230 --> 00:04:33,857
- Bye, Dad.
- Bye.

43
00:04:34,357 --> 00:04:35,650
See you, Mikey.

44
00:04:35,817 --> 00:04:37,027
Bye, Henry.

45
00:04:37,194 --> 00:04:39,362
HENRY'S MOTHER: Henry! Watch how you cross!

46
00:04:39,529 --> 00:04:40,781
Bring back milk!

47
00:04:40,947 --> 00:04:44,075
HENRY: <i>My mother was happy after
she found out that the Ciceros...</i>

48
00:04:44,242 --> 00:04:47,788
<i>came from the same part of Sicily
as she did. To my mother...</i>

49
00:04:47,954 --> 00:04:50,749
<i>that was the answer to all her prayers.</i>

50
00:04:52,459 --> 00:04:54,669
<i>I was the luckiest kid in the world.</i>

51
00:04:54,836 --> 00:04:57,672
<i>I could go anywhere, I could do anything.</i>

52
00:04:57,839 --> 00:05:00,509
<i>I knew everybody, and everybody knew me.</i>

53
00:05:00,967 --> 00:05:03,720
<i>Wiseguys would pull up
and Tuddy would toss me their keys...</i>

54
00:05:03,887 --> 00:05:05,639
<i>and let me park their Cadillacs.</i>

55
00:05:05,806 --> 00:05:09,392
<i>Here I am, this little kid,
I can't even see over the steering wheel...</i>

56
00:05:09,559 --> 00:05:11,728
<i>and I'm parking Cadillacs.</i>

57
00:05:14,981 --> 00:05:17,108
<i>But it wasn't too long...</i>

58
00:05:17,275 --> 00:05:21,071
<i>before my parents changed
their minds about my job at the cabstand.</i>

59
00:05:21,238 --> 00:05:22,864
For your mother and sister.

60
00:05:23,031 --> 00:05:26,409
HENRY: <i>For them, the cabstand was
supposed to be a part-time job. But for me...</i>

61
00:05:26,576 --> 00:05:28,537
<i>it was definitely full-time.</i>

62
00:05:28,703 --> 00:05:30,622
<i>That's all I wanted to do.</i>

63
00:05:30,789 --> 00:05:34,960
<i>People like my father could never
understand, but I was a part of something.</i>

64
00:05:35,126 --> 00:05:37,921
<i>I belonged. I was treated like a grown-up.</i>

65
00:05:38,755 --> 00:05:40,257
Tell him 519.

66
00:05:40,507 --> 00:05:42,425
HENRY: <i>Every day I was learning to score.</i>

67
00:05:42,592 --> 00:05:45,095
<i>A dollar here, a dollar there.</i>

68
00:05:45,262 --> 00:05:47,180
<i>I was living in a fantasy.</i>

69
00:05:47,347 --> 00:05:49,391
[MEN CHATTERING]

70
00:05:49,724 --> 00:05:51,268
Did you have a good day at school?

71
00:05:51,434 --> 00:05:53,228
HENRY: <i>My father was always pissed off.</i>

72
00:05:53,395 --> 00:05:55,522
<i>Pissed that he made such lousy money...</i>

73
00:05:55,689 --> 00:05:58,608
<i>pissed that my kid brother Michael
was in a wheelchair.</i>

74
00:05:58,775 --> 00:06:03,029
<i>He was pissed that there were seven of us
living in such a tiny house.</i>

75
00:06:03,446 --> 00:06:04,906
Tell me about this.

76
00:06:05,574 --> 00:06:07,617
It's a letter from school.

77
00:06:08,118 --> 00:06:10,954
It says you haven't been there in months.

78
00:06:12,205 --> 00:06:13,540
In months!

79
00:06:13,707 --> 00:06:14,875
[HENRY'S MOTHER SCREAMING]

80
00:06:15,041 --> 00:06:16,668
You're a bum!

81
00:06:16,835 --> 00:06:19,087
Want to grow up to be a burn?

82
00:06:20,630 --> 00:06:24,801
HENRY: <i>After a while, he was mostly pissed
because I hung around the cabstand.</i>

83
00:06:24,968 --> 00:06:26,845
<i>He knew what went on at that cabstand.</i>

84
00:06:27,012 --> 00:06:31,641
<i>Every once in a while, I'd have to take
a beating. But by then, I didn't care.</i>

85
00:06:31,975 --> 00:06:33,685
<i>The way I saw it...</i>

86
00:06:34,019 --> 00:06:36,646
<i>everybody takes a beating sometime.</i>

87
00:06:37,939 --> 00:06:41,860
- I can't make any more deliveries.
- What? You'll fuck everything up.

88
00:06:42,027 --> 00:06:43,945
My dad says he'll kill me. Look.

89
00:06:44,112 --> 00:06:45,405
Come on with me.

90
00:06:45,697 --> 00:06:47,616
MAN: Is that him, kid? 
HENRY: No.

91
00:06:48,283 --> 00:06:49,993
- MAN: How about him?
- No.

92
00:06:51,995 --> 00:06:54,039
- That's the guy.
- Get him.

93
00:06:55,832 --> 00:06:57,167
Excuse me.

94
00:06:58,335 --> 00:07:01,004
- Scumbag.
- Come here, you piece of shit.

95
00:07:08,803 --> 00:07:10,931
- Know this kid?
- Yeah.

96
00:07:11,097 --> 00:07:12,766
- TUDDY: Know where he lives?
- Yeah.

97
00:07:12,933 --> 00:07:15,060
TUDDY: You deliver mail to his house?
MAILMAN: Yeah.

98
00:07:15,226 --> 00:07:19,064
TUDDY: From now on, any letter from that
school to his house comes directly here.

99
00:07:19,230 --> 00:07:20,523
- Understand? 
- MAILMAN: Yeah.

100
00:07:20,690 --> 00:07:23,276
TUDDY: Another letter from that school
goes to that kid's house...

101
00:07:23,443 --> 00:07:25,820
in the fucking oven you'll go, head first.

102
00:07:25,987 --> 00:07:30,283
HENRY: <i>That was it. No more letters from
truant officers. No letters from school.</i>

103
00:07:30,450 --> 00:07:32,535
<i>In fact, no more letters from anybody.</i>

104
00:07:32,702 --> 00:07:36,498
<i>Finally after a few weeks, my mother
went to the post office to complain.</i>

105
00:07:36,831 --> 00:07:38,500
<i>How could I go to school after that...</i>

106
00:07:38,667 --> 00:07:42,796
<i>and pledge allegiance to the flag
and sit through good government bullshit?</i>

107
00:07:45,882 --> 00:07:49,052
<i>Paulie hated phones.
He wouldn't have one in his house.</i>

108
00:07:49,219 --> 00:07:51,888
Mickey called. Want me to call him back?

109
00:07:52,263 --> 00:07:53,890
All right, make the call.

110
00:07:54,057 --> 00:07:57,644
HENRY: <i>He got all his calls second hand.
Then you'd have to call the people back...</i>

111
00:07:57,811 --> 00:07:58,853
<i>from an outside phone.</i>

112
00:07:59,020 --> 00:08:01,481
Got a nickel? Get him on the phone.

113
00:08:02,232 --> 00:08:06,987
HENRY: <i>There were guys, that's all they did
all day, was take care of Paulie's calls.</i>

114
00:08:13,243 --> 00:08:15,578
[CHATTERING]

115
00:08:16,621 --> 00:08:20,917
<i>For a guy who moved all day long,
Paulie didn't talk to six people.</i>

116
00:08:21,084 --> 00:08:24,087
<i>If there was a union problem
or, say, a beef in the numbers...</i>

117
00:08:24,254 --> 00:08:27,757
<i>only the top guys could meet
with Paulie to discuss the problem.</i>

118
00:08:27,924 --> 00:08:31,177
<i>Everything was one-on-one.
Paulie hated conferences.</i>

119
00:08:31,928 --> 00:08:34,389
<i>He didn't want anybody hearing what he said...</i>

120
00:08:34,556 --> 00:08:37,851
<i>and he didn't want anybody listening
to what he was being told.</i>

121
00:08:38,018 --> 00:08:42,272
<i>Hundreds of guys depended on Paulie,
he got a piece of everything they made.</i>

122
00:08:42,439 --> 00:08:46,776
<i>It was a tribute, like in the old country,
except they were doing it in America.</i>

123
00:08:46,943 --> 00:08:51,406
<i>All they got from Paulie was protection
from other guys looking to rip them off.</i>

124
00:08:51,573 --> 00:08:55,493
<i>That's what it's all about. That's what
the FBI could never understand.</i>

125
00:08:55,952 --> 00:08:58,121
<i>What Paulie and the Organization does...</i>

126
00:08:58,288 --> 00:09:02,208
<i>is offer protection for people
who can't go to the cops. That's it.</i>

127
00:09:02,792 --> 00:09:06,921
<i>That's all it is. They're like
the police department for wiseguys.</i>

128
00:09:07,130 --> 00:09:08,423
[GLASS SHATTERING]

129
00:09:16,723 --> 00:09:20,810
<i>People looked at me differently,
and they knew I was with somebody.</i>

130
00:09:20,977 --> 00:09:25,440
<i>I didn't have to wait in line at the bakery
on Sunday mornings for fresh bread.</i>

131
00:09:25,607 --> 00:09:26,858
<i>The owner knew who I was with...</i>

132
00:09:27,025 --> 00:09:30,403
<i>and he'd come from around the counter.
No matter how many were waiting...</i>

133
00:09:30,570 --> 00:09:32,572
<i>I was taken care of first.</i>

134
00:09:32,822 --> 00:09:35,158
<i>Our neighbours didn't park
in our driveway anymore...</i>

135
00:09:35,325 --> 00:09:38,161
<i>even though we didn't have a car. At 13...</i>

136
00:09:38,328 --> 00:09:40,997
<i>I was making more money than most
of the grown-ups around.</i>

137
00:09:41,164 --> 00:09:44,292
<i>I had more money than I could spend.
I had it all.</i>

138
00:09:54,427 --> 00:09:59,099
<i>One day, some neighborhood kids carried
my mother's groceries all the way home.</i>

139
00:09:59,265 --> 00:10:00,683
<i>You know why?</i>

140
00:10:01,518 --> 00:10:03,353
<i>It was out of respect.</i>

141
00:10:05,105 --> 00:10:07,190
Hi, Mom, what do you think?

142
00:10:08,817 --> 00:10:11,528
- Look at my shoes, aren't they great?
- My God.

143
00:10:12,070 --> 00:10:13,696
You look like a gangster.

144
00:10:13,863 --> 00:10:15,532
They shot me. Help!

145
00:10:15,949 --> 00:10:17,992
[MAN YELLING]

146
00:10:18,159 --> 00:10:19,953
TUDDY: Henry, shut the door.

147
00:10:20,954 --> 00:10:24,249
HENRY: <i>That was the first time
I had ever seen anyone shot.</i>

148
00:10:25,041 --> 00:10:27,460
Can't have that in here. Jesus Christ!

149
00:10:27,627 --> 00:10:29,254
I can't have that in this joint.

150
00:10:29,420 --> 00:10:31,214
HENRY: <i>I remember feeling bad about the guy...</i>

151
00:10:31,381 --> 00:10:34,509
<i>but I also remember feeling
that maybe Tuddy was right.</i>

152
00:10:34,759 --> 00:10:37,387
<i>I knew Paulie didn't want
anybody dying in the building.</i>

153
00:10:37,554 --> 00:10:41,391
You're a real jerk. You wasted
eight fucking aprons on this guy.

154
00:10:41,558 --> 00:10:44,727
What the hell's wrong with you?
I got to toughen this kid up.

155
00:11:04,497 --> 00:11:06,416
HENRY: <i>It was a glorious time.</i>

156
00:11:07,333 --> 00:11:09,919
<i>And wiseguys were all over the place.</i>

157
00:11:10,879 --> 00:11:13,840
<i>It was before Apalachin and before Crazy Joe...</i>

158
00:11:14,007 --> 00:11:16,926
<i>decided to take on a boss and start a war.</i>

159
00:11:17,594 --> 00:11:19,637
<i>It was when I met the world.</i>

160
00:11:19,804 --> 00:11:22,515
<i>And it was when I first met Jimmy Conway.</i>

161
00:11:23,975 --> 00:11:27,145
<i>He couldn't have been more than 28 or 29
at the time...</i>

162
00:11:27,312 --> 00:11:29,230
<i>but he was already a legend.</i>

163
00:11:29,397 --> 00:11:33,401
<i>He'd walk in the door and everybody
who worked the room just went wild.</i>

164
00:11:33,568 --> 00:11:36,154
<i>He'd give the doorman $100
just for opening the door.</i>

165
00:11:36,321 --> 00:11:40,241
<i>He'd give hundreds to the dealers
and the guys who ran the games.</i>

166
00:11:40,408 --> 00:11:43,369
<i>The bartender got $100
just for keeping the ice cubes cold.</i>

167
00:11:43,536 --> 00:11:46,623
The Irishman is here
to take all you guineas' money.

168
00:11:49,834 --> 00:11:52,587
- Want a drink?
- Give me a 7 and 7.

169
00:11:59,719 --> 00:12:03,097
- I'd like you to meet the kid Henry.
- How you doing?

170
00:12:05,475 --> 00:12:08,186
- Thank you.
- Keep them coming.

171
00:12:08,353 --> 00:12:11,356
HENRY: <i>Jimmy was one of the most
feared guys in the city.</i>

172
00:12:11,522 --> 00:12:13,149
<i>He was first locked up at 11...</i>

173
00:12:13,316 --> 00:12:16,402
<i>and he was doing hits
for mob bosses when he was 16.</i>

174
00:12:16,569 --> 00:12:19,364
<i>See, hits never bothered Jimmy. It was business.</i>

175
00:12:19,822 --> 00:12:21,908
<i>But what Jimmy really loved to</i> do...

176
00:12:22,075 --> 00:12:24,118
<i>what he really loved to do was steal.</i>

177
00:12:24,285 --> 00:12:26,454
<i>He actually enjoyed it.</i>

178
00:12:26,621 --> 00:12:30,541
<i>Jimmy was the kind of guy who rooted
for the bad guys in the movies.</i>

179
00:12:31,251 --> 00:12:33,002
Give me your wallet.

180
00:12:36,005 --> 00:12:39,175
You might know who we are,
but we know who you are. Understand?

181
00:12:39,342 --> 00:12:41,719
HENRY: <i>He was one of
the city's biggest hijackers...</i>

182
00:12:41,886 --> 00:12:45,348
<i>of booze, cigarettes, razor blades,
shrimp and lobsters.</i>

183
00:12:45,515 --> 00:12:48,643
<i>Shrimp and lobsters were best.
They went really fast.</i>

184
00:12:48,810 --> 00:12:52,605
<i>Almost all of them were gimmies.
They just gave it up, no problem.</i>

185
00:12:52,772 --> 00:12:54,440
<i>They called him Jimmy the Gent.</i>

186
00:12:54,607 --> 00:12:55,733
Help the lady.

187
00:12:55,900 --> 00:12:58,194
HENRY: <i>Drivers loved him.
They used to tip him off...</i>

188
00:12:58,361 --> 00:13:01,698
<i>about the really good loads.
Of course, everybody got a piece.</i>

189
00:13:01,864 --> 00:13:03,950
WOMAN: Thanks, I'll be back for the rest later.

190
00:13:04,117 --> 00:13:05,535
JIMMY: Okay, see you later.

191
00:13:08,037 --> 00:13:09,706
Henry, come here.

192
00:13:10,623 --> 00:13:12,667
- Say hello to Tommy.
- How're you doing, Henry?

193
00:13:12,834 --> 00:13:14,836
You're gonna be working together, okay?

194
00:13:15,003 --> 00:13:16,713
Help him. Go ahead.

195
00:13:17,088 --> 00:13:19,382
Jimmy, you got anything good?

196
00:13:19,549 --> 00:13:23,594
HENRY: <i>And when the cops assigned a
whole army to stop Jimmy, what did he do?</i>

197
00:13:23,761 --> 00:13:24,804
JIMMY: How're you doing?

198
00:13:24,971 --> 00:13:26,681
HENRY: <i>He made them partners.</i>

199
00:13:26,848 --> 00:13:28,474
I'd complain, but who'd listen?

200
00:13:28,808 --> 00:13:30,435
- MAN 1: One Pall Mall. 
- HENRY: There you go.

201
00:13:30,601 --> 00:13:32,687
- What do you need? 
- MAN 2: Two Luckies.

202
00:13:32,854 --> 00:13:34,731
- TOMMY: Here you go, Henry.
- Thanks a lot.

203
00:13:34,897 --> 00:13:35,940
What do you need?

204
00:13:36,107 --> 00:13:38,735
- One Pall Mall.
- One Pall Mall, here you go.

205
00:13:38,901 --> 00:13:40,570
- What are you doing?
- It's all right.

206
00:13:40,737 --> 00:13:43,740
- You have permission from your mother?
- How many cartons you need?

207
00:13:43,906 --> 00:13:46,951
- Where'd you get the cigarettes?
- Get him out of here.

208
00:13:47,118 --> 00:13:48,745
- It's okay.
- It's not okay.

209
00:13:48,911 --> 00:13:52,290
HENRY: You don't understand.
MAN: You don't understand. Store's closed.

210
00:13:57,128 --> 00:13:58,963
- Henry got pinched.
- Where?

211
00:13:59,130 --> 00:14:00,798
By the factory, selling cigarettes.

212
00:14:00,965 --> 00:14:04,927
MAN: <i>Henry Hill. The People of
the State of New York vs. Henry Hill.</i>

213
00:14:05,219 --> 00:14:08,014
Docket number 704162.

214
00:14:09,098 --> 00:14:11,392
Uh, yes, sir. That's me.

215
00:14:14,187 --> 00:14:16,939
Just stand there. Now stay there.

216
00:14:23,363 --> 00:14:25,114
Counselor, proceed.

217
00:14:28,117 --> 00:14:29,744
Congratulations.

218
00:14:30,036 --> 00:14:31,871
